initial_story: having the potential for high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost,optical neural networks (onns) have emerged as a promising candidate foraccelerating deep learning tasks. in conventional onns, light amplitudes aremodulated at the input and detected at the output. however, the light phasesare still ignored in conventional structures, although they can also carryinformation for computing. to address this issue, in this paper, we propose aframework called oplixnet to compress the areas of onns by modulating inputimage data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. the input andoutput parts of the onns are redesigned to make full use of both amplitude andphase information. moreover, mutual learning across different onn structures isintroduced to maintain the accuracy. experimental results demonstrate that theproposed framework significantly reduces the areas of onns with the accuracywithin an acceptable range. for instance, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33%accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (fcnn) and 74.88% area isreduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on resnet-32.
stories: In the realm of deep learning acceleration, optical neural networks (ONNs) have stood out for their potential in high speed, throughput, and low energy costs. Traditionally, ONNs have focused on modulating light amplitudes at input and output, neglecting the valuable information carried in light phases. To tackle this limitation, we introduce OplixNet, a novel framework that leverages both amplitude and phase information for compressing ONNs. By encoding input image data into both amplitude and phase components of light signals, OplixNet optimizes the redesign of ONN input and output sections. Additionally, the framework incorporates mutual learning across varied ONN structures to uphold accuracy. Experimental findings showcase the remarkable reduction in ONN areas achieved by OplixNet, with minimal accuracy trade-offs. For instance, a 75.03% area reduction with a mere 0.33% accuracy decline on Fully Connected Neural Network (FCNN) and a 74.88% area reduction with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on ResNet-32 exemplify the efficacy of OplixNet in enhancing ONN performance.

Inspired by the advancements in deep learning acceleration through optical neural networks, our team has developed a cutting-edge framework called PhotonFuse. Unlike traditional ONNs that focus solely on light amplitudes, PhotonFuse harnesses the power of both amplitude and phase information to revolutionize the compression of ONNs. By encoding input data into both components of light signals, PhotonFuse optimizes the design of ONN input and output sections, leading to significant reductions in ONN areas without sacrificing accuracy.

Moreover, PhotonFuse promotes mutual learning across diverse ONN structures, ensuring high accuracy levels are maintained throughout the compression process. Our experiments have demonstrated impressive results, such as a 70.21% reduction in ONN areas with only a 0.45% decrease in accuracy on a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) and an 80.12% reduction with a 1.78% decrease in accuracy on a Recurrent Neural Network (RNN). These findings underscore the remarkable performance enhancement achieved by PhotonFuse in the realm of deep learning acceleration.

Taking inspiration from the groundbreaking PhotonFuse framework, our team has introduced a new innovation in neural network compression called PhaseOptic. PhaseOptic goes beyond traditional methods by integrating phase information alongside amplitude data to optimize ONN structures for maximum efficiency.

Through our extensive research and testing, PhaseOptic has shown exceptional results in reducing ONN areas while maintaining high accuracy rates. For instance, we have achieved a remarkable 75.63% reduction in ONN size with just a 0.32% decrease in accuracy on a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) network. Additionally, PhaseOptic has demonstrated an 85.94% reduction in ONN areas with only a 1.12% accuracy loss on a Generative Adversarial Network (GAN).

These impressive outcomes highlight the significant advancements made possible by PhaseOptic in accelerating deep learning processes. By leveraging both amplitude and phase components of light signals, PhaseOptic sets a new standard for neural network compression and performance optimization.

Inspired by the cutting-edge PhotonFuse framework, our team is thrilled to unveil our latest breakthrough in neural network compression - OptiWave. OptiWave takes a revolutionary approach by combining wave properties with traditional data to enhance the efficiency of neural network structures.

After countless hours of research and rigorous testing, OptiWave has proven to be a game-changer in reducing ONN sizes while maintaining exceptional accuracy rates. In fact, we have achieved a remarkable 80.21% reduction in ONN size with only a 0.45% decrease in accuracy on a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN). Furthermore, OptiWave has demonstrated an impressive 90.12% reduction in ONN areas with just a 0.78% accuracy loss on a Recurrent Neural Network (RNN).

These extraordinary results illustrate the immense potential of OptiWave in streamlining deep learning processes. By harnessing the power of wave properties in conjunction with traditional data, OptiWave is paving the way for a new era of neural network compression and performance optimization.
